{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"b523f06a-cf7f-4844-a6cd-2811e2d602db","content":"On macOS, when a NativeAOT app crashes, look in these places:\n\n1. **Apple Crash Reports** — macOS automatically generates `.ips` or `.crash` files:\n   ```\n   ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   /Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n\n2. **Console.app** — Open it and check **Crash Reports** in the sidebar for the same files with a GUI.\n\n3. **Core dumps** — If enabled (`ulimit -c unlimited` before running), they land in `/cores/core.<pid>`. You can then inspect with `lldb`:\n   ```\n   lldb --core /cores/core.12345 ./YourApp\n   ```\n\n**Key tip:** Core dumps are disabled by default on macOS. Set `ulimit -c unlimited` in the shell *before* launching your app to ensure one is written on crash. SIP (System Integrity Protection) can also block core dumps for some paths.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"1bfbc5ac-dfc8-4321-9238-42c481cc6036","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT .NET application on macOS, without `createdump`. This is a general knowledge question — no tools needed.","outputTokens":289,"requestId":"6094:14BF27:2D7E0F:3B4B47:69FFE421"},"id":"5fe9f362-d820-47d6-89fd-22a70ff832b3","timestamp":"2026-05-10T01:49:30.618Z","parentId":"b5e6a74e-bd32-4906-8b14-ebb5d90e95c4"}
